Kenya's economy is expected to grow 5.8 per cent in Q2 2019 before finishing the year strong at an average of six per cent, Central Bank of Kenya has said. The growth although lower compared to last year is pegged generally stable microeconomics, with supported by political stability. According to CBK governor Patrick Njoroge, lending to private sector has improved to 6.3 per cent from 5 per cent i July, stimulating activities for SMEs. He however cited interest cap law, ongoing global trade wars between US and China,delayed clearance of bills in counties and national government and eratic rainfall as risks to the economic growth.